title: For Trade:  Ruger LCP .380 with LaserLyte side mount laser for trade only
postcontent:
For trade is this Ruger LCP .380 Auto pistol. I am only interested in a trade at this time for a Walther PPK. I am not particular on a stainless steel or blued model PPK, just so long as the pistol if in good operational order. I would prefer the Smith & Wesson over the Interarms model as I have a large collection of Smiths. ?
This pistol includes the following:
•	Ruger LCP .380 Auto Pistol (Blued)
•	One magazine with extended finger grip 
o	Spare non-finger grip magazine base 
•	LaserLyte SML Ruger/Kel-Tec .380 - CK-AMF
o	Spare batteries
o	Sight tool
o	Owner’s manual
•	Original box
•	Original owner’s manual
•	Original lock and keys
•	Original fired casing and documents
•	Original Ruger zipper pouch
•	50 rounds of ammo
Additional information about the Ruger LCP 380: http://www.ruger.com/products/lcp/index.html 
Weighing just 9.4 oz (266.5 g) this is Ruger's first entry into the field of tiny, ultra-light defensive pistols.[4] LCP stands for "Lightweight Compact Pistol" and was designed in direct response to customer requests for a compact firearm for use by police as a back-up, and as a defensive handgun for civilian concealed carry needs.[5]
The pistol has a glass-filled nylon frame, a two-finger grip, and a through-hardened blued steel slide. It is similar in appearance to the Kel-Tec P-3AT which weighs 8.3 oz. and uses a similar tension spring for the lightweight hammer, identical locked breech mechanism, and similar takedown method. The main differences are the Glock style extractor and the incorporation of an external slide stop. It is possible to tell if there is a round chambered by looking at the "view hole" next to the extractor
Additional information about the Laserlyte laser: http://www.laserlyte.com/products/ck-amf
LaserLyte answers the growing demand for lasers specific to the increasingly popular conceal carry market with the new Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser (CK-AMF). At half the cost of a leading competitor, the CK-AMF fits on the side of the Ruger LCP and the Kel-Tec .380 and .32. Easy to mount on the gun by simply pushing out and replacing the stock pins with the new screws (included).  Then push the ergonomic activation button with the index finger and the laser is on target. The CK-AMF design works also as a finger guide that allows for safe trigger control without blocking the laser beam. The programmable laser features a pulse or constant on mode and also has an auto-off function to prevent an unwanted battery drain. The side mounted laser allows the pistol to fit in virtually any nylon pocket holster. The new LaserLyte Ruger LCP Side Mount Laser is compact and light, and foremost – deadly.
Thanks for looking and if you’re interested, please email me.
Dave

title: For Sale:  Sig 522 Classic *PRICE DROP*
postcontent:
Sig 522 for sale. Bought new, a little over a year old, good condition except for what is mostly a cosmetic issue. 

I was trying to do a modification to the storage tube inside of the 'gas block' (its not really a gas block and is purely aesthetic, its what would be the gas block on the sig 556) to mount a laser sight in there. Unfortunately, I sheered off a screw tap and haven't been able to get it out due to lacking the proper tools to do so. I also had to cut the storage tube off to allow the front end piece to be snapped back into place as a result. The end result of this whole thing is there is a screw tap snapped off inside of the cosmetic-only " gas block " and it no longer has a storage tube. When the front end-cap is in place, you can't tell that anything is wrong.

Function is flawless and I would never have attempted the above if there were any chance that it would effect function. With the proper tools it shouldn't be hard to get the tap out and finish the mod. A cheap laser sight to use for that purpose is included and is mounted on the front rail.

Also includes a foregrip and a total of 3 Sig 26 round magazines and a BSA red dot. Also it has the tri-rails mounted on the front of the grip, these too, are an option and don't come on the gun new. This thing has fired every 22lr I have thrown at it. It runs excellently.

This is probably the best of the 'tacticool' 22s, in my opinion. 

Because of the cosmetic issue I'm going to let it go pretty cheap for a Sig 522. First $325 gets it. (They are $450+ New without said accessories.)

I have an M&P listed in the Handguns section too. Whichever goes first wins, I keep the other.

I am in Steubenville but don't mind a moderate drive to meet halfway. This is my one and only price drop on this gun.

Has the triangle and arrow stamping (from a de-milled military rifle). Barrel is a Romanian new-manufacture and chrome-lined. Bore is in very very great condition. Total round count is exactly 600. I've had absolutely 0 malfunctions. Cleaned and lubed after each shooting session. It's been well taken care of. I've had this up for while before, but nothing has come up that interested me, so I held onto it for a while longer. Now I think it's time to fish around for some offers again.

-Degreased and coated it with black engine enamel. Its held up fine to solvents and oil, but shows wear in the usual places like the safety switch and dust cover.
-Epoxied a small shim on the inside of the magwell to eliminate mag wobble. There wasn't a lot of mag wobble before, and it ran perfectly fine before too. It just annoyed me.

Comes with:
-5 steel mags, 1 Tapco 20-rounder

title: For Sale:  Antique German Zimmerscheutzen target rifle
postcontent:
Up for sale is a neat old Zimmerscheutzen target rifle, in 5.4mm Flobert, with a loading port halfway up the barrel because the weak target cartridge can't traverse a full length rifle barrel. Also interestingly enough uses a linkage attached to the hammer to run a striker that passes down the barrel to the loading port.

A neat example of old world craftsmanship.

The downside is the stock's been refinished, the rear sight stalk is broken off, and the loading port breech is missing. Salvageable for parts, restorable if you can find or make a new breech tab, or a neat wall-hanger.

title: For Sale:  Interwar continental Austrian/German 7x57 stalking rifle
postcontent:
Up for sale is a really neat piece, a presumably 1920s sporter.

The rifle was originally a Steyr 1912 Mexican contract Mauser '98 in 7x57, but those rifles were used by the Austro-Hungarians in WW1, after which it appears some German or Austrian gunsmith or tinkerer of moderate skill began to customize, but due to the Great Depression didn't have the money to do a classic bespoke customization job on.

It's got a bent-and-spooned bolt, of a not particularly elegant but serviceable job. It also has express sight leaves, a double set-trigger, and a recontoured and spliced military stock that bears the traditional Germanic styling.

Mirror bright bore, a good shooter, but I've got entirely too many hunting rifles and projects.

title: For Sale:  Sig 522 Classic *PRICE DROP*
postcontent:
Sig 522 for sale. Bought new, a little over a year old, good condition except for what is mostly a cosmetic issue. 

I was trying to do a modification to the storage tube inside of the 'gas block' (its not really a gas block and is purely aesthetic, its what would be the gas block on the sig 556) to mount a laser sight in there. Unfortunately, I sheered off a screw tap and haven't been able to get it out due to lacking the proper tools to do so. I also had to cut the storage tube off to allow the front end piece to be snapped back into place as a result. The end result of this whole thing is there is a screw tap snapped off inside of the cosmetic-only " gas block " and it no longer has a storage tube. When the front end-cap is in place, you can't tell that anything is wrong.

Function is flawless and I would never have attempted the above if there were any chance that it would effect function. With the proper tools it shouldn't be hard to get the tap out and finish the mod. A cheap laser sight to use for that purpose is included and is mounted on the front rail.

Also includes a foregrip and a total of 3 Sig 26 round magazines and a BSA red dot. Also it has the tri-rails mounted on the front of the grip, these too, are an option and don't come on the gun new. I'll throw in some 22lr ammo as well to get you going in the unlikely event you don't already have a 22lr gun.

This thing has fired every 22lr I have thrown at it. It runs excellently.

This is probably the best of the 'tacticool' 22s, in my opinion. 

Because of the cosmetic issue I'm going to let it go pretty cheap for a Sig 522. First $300 gets it. (They are $450+ New without said accessories.)

This is an absolute rock bottom price.

Must be willing to meet within a 1hr drive of Steubenville (43952).

Must sell by tomorrow morning.
